Set Working Directory

- Be sure to set working directory

We will be using a very known dataset mtcars (Motor Trend Car Road Test). This data was extracted from the 1974 Motor Trend US magazine, and comprises fuel consumption and 10 aspects of automobile design and performance for 32 automobiles (197374 models).

  • mpg: Miles/(US) gallon
  • cyl: Number of cylinders
  • disp: Displacement (cu.in)
  • hp: Gross horsepower
  • drat: Rear axle ratio
  • wt: Weight (1000 lbs)
  • qsec: 1/4 mile time
  • vs: Engine (0=V-shaped; 1=straight)
  • am: Transmission (0=automatic; 1=manual)
  • gear: Number of forward gears
  • carb: Number of carburetors

Data visualization

# a quick way to show all relationships among variables in a dataset
# Here we use 5 variables in the mtcars dataset. 'pairs.panels()' in 'psych' package.
mt5<- mtcars %>% select(mpg,disp, hp,wt,cyl)
pairs.panels(mt5, lm=TRUE)

## [1] 32 11
# running a principal component analysis (PCA) using 'prcomp()' function on mtcars data, removing "vs" and "am" which are
# categorical(binary) variables which are not recommended with PCA and "mpg" which is the response variable
pca_mt = prcomp(formula = ~ cyl + disp + hp + drat + wt + qsec + gear + carb , data = mt, center = TRUE, scale = TRUE)
# display the output of PCA on 'mroz'
summary(pca_mt)

Clustering and Classification

Clustering: k-means (unsupervised learning)

# use 'kmeans()' function to find k-clusters; note: we need to specifiy the number of clusters 'centers' (our k).
# 'nstart' specifies number of initializations (with starting centeroids randomly placed) of k-means algorithm.

wss <- rep(NA, 10)
for(k in c(1:10)) {
  wss[k] = kmeans(mtsub, k, nstart=10)$tot.withinss
}
plot(wss, type="b", xlab="Number of clusters", ylab="Total within-cluster sum of squares")

km_mt2 = kmeans(mtsub, centers =2, nstart = 10)

# k-means plot using 'fviz_cluster' in 'factoextra' package will show the observations in two clusters
fviz_cluster(km_mt2, data = mtsub, repel = TRUE,
             palette = c("navy","magenta"),
             ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
             main = "Two clusters on the plane of first two PCs of 'mtsub'.")

km_mt3 = kmeans(mtsub, centers =3, nstart = 10)

# k-means plot using 'fviz_cluster' in 'factoextra' package will show the observations in three clusters
fviz_cluster(km_mt3, data = mtsub, repel = TRUE,
             palette = c("navy","magenta","green"),
             ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
             main = "Three clusters on the plane of first two PCs of 'mtsub'.")

Classification: logistic regression (supervised learning)

- We will use our familiar example of titanic.

# read 'titanic.csv' file into data frame object 'titanic_raw'.
titanic_raw <- read.csv("~/Dropbox/Teaching/TBA2102/AY2021/Inclass Lecture/lecture 9/titanic.csv", header = TRUE)
titanic_selected <- subset(titanic_raw, select = c("survived", "sex", "age", "sibsp", "parch", "fare", "embarked"))
titanic <- na.omit(titanic_selected)

# use 'glm()' with specified parameter 'family = binomial' for logistic regression
fit_surv <- glm(survived ~ sex + age + sibsp + parch + fare + embarked, family = binomial, data = titanic, control = list(maxit = 50))

# display the output of logistic regression
summary(fit_surv)

# now we shall predict the survival probability using our fitted model. 
# note that 'type = response' will compute the probability of survival for us on the scale of the response variable.
predprob_surv = predict(fit_surv, type = 'response') 

# let's fix our rule for defining `survival`: survived = 1 when predicted probability >= 0.5, 0 otherwise; create a new variable 'pred_surv' as predicted survival of our cases in the data.
pred_surv = ifelse(predprob_surv >= 0.5, 1, 0)

# Classfication (or Confusion) Matrix
# a quick look at how many predicted survival agrees with actual observed survival
sum(pred_surv == titanic$survived)
## [1] 702
# observation: 702 out of 889 successful prediction.

# 'pred_surv' and 'titanic$survived' are still numeric obj, let's convert them to factors.
pred_surv = factor(pred_surv, labels = c('Not Survived', 'Survived'))
titanic$survived = factor(titanic$survived, labels = c('Not Survived', 'Survived'))
# using 'confusionMatrix()' function in R to generate classification or confusion matrix to evaluate our logit classifier.
cm = confusionMatrix(pred_surv, titanic$survived, positive = 'Survived')
# display the classification matrix
print(cm)
